Imagine you have a tiny, specially designed plastic Tupperware container. Its physical dimensions are built perfectly to hold 
exactly one standard slice of pizza. Not a millimeter more. This tiny container represents the byte data type. In computer memory, 
a byte is a very small box that takes up exactly 8 bits of space, which means it can only hold numbers from 0 up to 255.

Now, imagine you try to shove a second slice of pizza into that exact same tiny container.

What happens? The lid won't close, the crust is crushed, and cheese starts spilling out over the sides. When the computer's processor 
notices this mess, it throws its hands up and yells: "Hey! You are exceeding the physical limits of the box you gave me! Your data is 
spilling into the void!" This "spill" is exactly what an OverflowException is.

## The Technical Reality

In programming, variables are like boxes of different sizes.

- A byte is a tiny box (holds 0 to 255).
- A short is a medium box (holds up to ~32,000).
- An int is a large box (holds up to ~2.1 billion).

When you try to take a massive number sitting comfortably in a large box (like an int) and force it into a tiny box (like a byte), 
the system realizes the tiny box cannot physically represent that number. To prevent data corruption—where the number gets silently 
chopped up and turns into garbage data—the runtime throws an OverflowException.

## Let's Look at the Code

// We have a massive number sitting in a large 'int' box.
// The 'int' box is huge, so 500 fits with plenty of room to spare.
int massiveNumber = 500; 

// Now, we try to force that 500 into a tiny 'byte' box.
// A byte box can only hold a maximum value of 255.
// BOOM! The lid won't close. OverflowException is thrown right here!
byte tinyBox = Convert.ToByte(massiveNumber);
